  "body": {
    "export_view": {
      "value": "<p>A recent RepairQ update reworks its browser cookie logic.  Because of this, some browsers may experience a loop when attempting to login.  To fix this, the old cookie needs to be deleted so a new one can generate.</p><p /><h2 id=\"LoginTroubleshooting-\ud83c\udf6aHowtoDeleteaSpecificCookiefromaWebsite\">\ud83c\udf6a How to Delete a Specific Cookie from a Website</h2><p>Use the steps below to delete a cookie <strong>just for one site</strong> (not all cookies).</p><h3 id=\"LoginTroubleshooting-\ud83d\udd35GoogleChrome\">\ud83d\udd35 Google Chrome</h3><ol start=\"1\"><li><p><strong>Open Chrome</strong> and go to the website.</p></li><li><p>Click the <strong>icon(lock or two lines with circles)</strong> to the <strong>left of the URL bar</strong>.</p></li><li><p>Click <strong>&quot;Cookies and site data&quot;</strong>.</p></li><li><p>In the popup, click <strong>&quot;Manage on-site device data\u201d</strong>.</p></li><li><p>You\u2019ll see a list of cookies grouped by domain.</p></li><li><p>Find repairq.io</p></li><li><p>Click <strong>&quot;Remove&quot;</strong> or the trash can icon.</p></li><li><p>Refresh the page to apply the change.</p></li></ol><p /><h3 id=\"LoginTroubleshooting-\ud83d\udfe3Safari(macOS)\">\ud83d\udfe3 Safari (macOS)</h3><blockquote><p>Safari doesn't have a lock icon with cookie access like Chrome or Edge. You\u2019ll need to go through <strong>Preferences</strong>.</p></blockquote><ol start=\"1\"><li><p>Open <strong>Safari</strong> and go to the website</p></li><li><p>Open <strong>Safari</strong> and go to <strong>Safari \u2192 Settings</strong> (or press <code>Cmd + ,</code>).</p></li><li><p>Click the <strong>&quot;Privacy&quot;</strong> tab.</p></li><li><p>Click <strong>&quot;Manage Website Data...&quot;</strong></p></li><li><p>In the search bar, type <strong>repairq.io</strong>.</p></li><li><p>Select <strong>repairq.io </strong>from the list.</p></li><li><p>Click <strong>&quot;Remove&quot;</strong></p></li><li><p>Click <strong>&quot;Done&quot;</strong>.</p></li><li><p>Refresh the page.</p></li></ol><p /><h3 id=\"LoginTroubleshooting-\ud83d\udd35MicrosoftEdge\">\ud83d\udd35 Microsoft Edge</h3><ol start=\"1\"><li><p>Open <strong>Edge</strong> and navigate to the website.</p></li><li><p>Click the <strong>lock icon</strong> to the <strong>left of the URL bar</strong>.</p></li><li><p>Click <strong>&quot;Cookies and Site Data&quot; </strong>then select <strong>\u201cCookies\u201d</strong>.</p></li><li><p>In the popup, you\u2019ll see a list of websites.</p></li><li><p>Select repairq.io</p></li><li><p>Click <strong>&quot;Remove&quot;</strong> or the trash icon.</p></li><li><p>Click <strong>&quot;Done&quot;</strong>, then refresh the site.</p></li></ol>",
